
[1]anagram

   AN'AGRAM, n. [Gr. a letter.]

   A transposition of the letters of a name, by which a new word is
   formed. Thus Galenus becomes angelus; William Noy, (attorney general to
   Charles I., a laborious man,) may be turned into I moyl in law.
